Chinese Ambassador Hosts Reception 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, April 22 (KCNA) -- Liu Xiaoming, Chinese ambassador to the DPRK, hosted a reception at his embassy on Monday in the run-up to the torch relay for the 29th Olympics to be held in Pyongyang. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present there on invitation were Yang Hyong Sop, vice-president of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, Pak Hak Son, chairman of the Physical Culture and Sports Guidance Commission who is chairman of the DPRK Olympic Committee, Pak Kwan O, chairman of the Pyongyang City People's Committee, and other officials concerned and diplomatic envoys of different countries here. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On hand were staff members of the Chinese embassy. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Chinese ambassador, addressing the reception, said that the torch relay would record a brilliant chapter in the history of the Olympics. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The torch relay to be held in Pyongyang would contribute to boosting the Sino-DPRK friendship and developing the exchange and cooperation in different fields between the two countries including sports and culture, he said. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Expressing heartfelt thanks to the Korean comrades for exerting positive efforts for the successful relay, he expressed belief that the relay would be successfully held. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Pak Hak Son in his speech said that the DPRK's friendly neighbor China's sponsorship of the 29th Olympics is not only the pride of the Chinese people but a pleasant event for the Korean people. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The torch relay to be held in Pyongyang would mark a significant occasion in developing the mutual cooperation and interaction on a higher level in the field of sports and demonstrating the traditional DPRK-China friendship, he said. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He stressed that the relay would prove a success thanks to the great concern of the Korean people who value the idea and spirit of the Olympics. �@�@�@

A-bomb Victims Interviewed 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, April 22 (KCNA) -- A-bomb victims in the DPRK were interviewed by foreign correspondents here and reporters of the General Association of Korean Residents in Japan at the People's Palace of Culture here Tuesday. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The secretary general of the Korean A-bomb Victims Association for Peace against Nukes spoke first. The secretary general said that the issue of A-bomb victims in the DPRK was a product of the Japanese imperialists' military occupation of Korea, adding that a great number of Koreans who were taken to Hiroshima and Nagasaki suffered from the explosion of A-bombs dropped by GIs. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The victims in the DPRK are entitled to get reparation and humanitarian aid, the speaker held, urging the Japanese government to make thorough-going apology and opt for providing prompt medical aid. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Pak Mun Suk, Ri Kye Son and Kim Myong Ae took the floor to testify before the attendants. They noted that due to the Japanese imperialists' colonial rule they suffered from the A-bomb explosion in an alien land and are still undergoing pain resulting from it. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They vehemently denounced the Japanese government for having neither made any apology to the Korean victims nor taken any measure in this respect. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They denounced Japan's hideous crimes against humanity in the name of the A-bomb victims and urged its government to opt for making reparation at an early date. �@�@�@

